WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

03:03.100 --> 03:07.311
This is what I get in return
for 30 years of service for my company?

03:07.604 --> 03:10.273
And they send some yo-yo 
like you in here

03:10.357 --> 03:12.817
to try to tell me that I'm out of a job?

03:12.901 --> 03:14.986
They should be telling you
you're out of a job.

03:15.070 --> 03:19.198
You have a lot of gall coming in here
and firing your number one producer.

03:19.283 --> 03:20.408
And then you're going
to go home tomorrow

03:20.492 --> 03:22.410
and make more money
than you've ever made in your life,

03:22.494 --> 03:24.662
and I'm going to go home
without a pay check. Fuck you.

03:24.746 --> 03:26.998
I just...
I guess you leave me dumbfounded.

03:27.082 --> 03:29.041
I don't know where this is coming from.

03:29.126 --> 03:30.710
How am I supposed to go back as a man

03:30.794 --> 03:33.004
and explain this to my wife
that I lost my job?

03:33.422 --> 03:35.131
On a stress level,

03:35.215 --> 03:39.135
I've heard that losing your job
is like a death in the family.

03:40.053 --> 03:43.055
But personally, I feel more like

03:44.308 --> 03:48.811
the people I worked with 
were my family and I died.

03:48.937 --> 03:53.399
I can't afford to be unemployed.
I have a house payment. I have children.

03:53.984 --> 03:56.402
I don't know how you can live
with yourself,

03:56.486 --> 03:59.822
but I'm sure that you'll find a way
while the rest of us are suffering.

03:59.907 --> 04:01.991
Who the fuck are you, man?

04:03.118 --> 04:05.745
<i>Excellent question. 
Who the fuck am I?</i>

04:06.330 --> 04:08.539
<i>Poor Steve has worked here
for seven years.</i>

04:08.832 --> 04:13.002
<i>He's never had a meeting with me
before or passed me in the hall</i>

04:13.086 --> 04:15.087
<i>or told me a story in the break room.</i>

04:15.172 --> 04:16.714
<i>And that's because I don't work here.</i>

04:16.798 --> 04:20.176
<i>I work for another company that lends me out 
to pussies like Steve's boss</i>

04:20.260 --> 04:22.637
<i>who don't have the balls
to sack their own employees,</i>

04:22.721 --> 04:24.513
<i>and in some cases, for good reason.</i>

04:24.598 --> 04:27.892
<i>Because people do crazy shit
when they get fired.</i>

04:32.481 --> 04:34.440
Did I do something wrong?

04:34.524 --> 04:36.692
I mean, is there something
I could do differently here?

04:36.777 --> 04:39.111
This is not an assessment
of your productivity.

04:39.196 --> 04:41.781
You gotta try not to take this personally.

04:42.199 --> 04:43.950
"Don't take it personally."

04:44.034 --> 04:46.953
Steven, I want you to review this packet.

04:47.037 --> 04:50.790
Take it seriously. I think you're gonna find 
a lot of good answers in here.

04:50.874 --> 04:53.501
I'm sure this is gonna be 
very helpful, a packet.

04:53.585 --> 04:55.753
Thank you. A packet.

04:59.549 --> 05:02.426
Well, anybody who ever built an empire
or changed the world

05:02.511 --> 05:04.804
sat where you are right now.

05:04.888 --> 05:08.224
And it's because they sat there
they were able to do it.

05:08.308 --> 05:10.059
That's the truth.

05:16.316 --> 05:18.567
I'm gonna need your keycard.

05:20.904 --> 05:22.196
Great. Okay.

05:22.280 --> 05:25.574
Now, I want you to take the day,
go get together your personal things,

05:25.659 --> 05:28.995
and then tomorrow,
you get yourself some exercise.

05:29.079 --> 05:30.496
You go out for a jog,

05:30.580 --> 05:34.750
you give yourself some routines,
and pretty soon you find your legs.

05:35.377 --> 05:36.711
How do I get in touch with you?

05:36.962 --> 05:38.838
Don't worry,
we'll be in touch with you soon.

05:38.922 --> 05:41.090
This is just the beginning.

05:42.175 --> 05:44.343
<i>I'll never see Steve again.</i>

06:02.529 --> 06:03.654
Thank you.

06:03.864 --> 06:05.865
<i>To know me is to fly with me.</i>

06:05.949 --> 06:07.950
<i>This is where I live.</i>

06:11.079 --> 06:14.081
<i>When I run my card, the system 
automatically prompts the desk clerk</i>

06:14.166 --> 06:16.250
<i>to greet me with this exact statement.</i> 

06:17.044 --> 06:18.878
Pleasure to see you again, Mr. Bingham.

06:18.962 --> 06:20.296
<i>It's these kinds of systemized,</i>

06:20.380 --> 06:23.382
<i>friendly touches
that keep my world in orbit.</i>

06:58.668 --> 07:00.961
<i>All the things you probably hate 
about traveling,</i>

07:01.046 --> 07:05.091
<i>the recycled air, the artificial lighting,
the digital juice dispensers,</i>

07:05.175 --> 07:08.803
<i>the cheap sushi,
are warm reminders that I'm home.</i>

07:22.526 --> 07:24.527
Do you want the cancer?

07:26.988 --> 07:29.323
- The what?
- Do you want the cancer?

07:29.407 --> 07:30.991
The cancer?

07:31.493 --> 07:33.285
The can, sir?

07:33.703 --> 07:36.205
No. I'm fine, thank you.

07:58.895 --> 08:00.855
How much does your life weigh?

08:02.732 --> 08:05.609
Imagine for a second
that you're carrying a backpack.

08:05.694 --> 08:08.362
I want you to feel the straps
on your shoulders.

08:08.864 --> 08:10.364
Feel them?

08:11.199 --> 08:14.493
Now I want you to pack it with all 
the stuff that you have in your life.

08:14.578 --> 08:18.164
You start with the little things,
the things on shelves and in drawers,

08:18.248 --> 08:20.875
the knickknacks, the collectibles.

08:21.168 --> 08:23.502
Feel the weight as that adds up.

08:23.587 --> 08:25.379
Then you start adding larger stuff,

08:25.463 --> 08:29.592
clothes, tabletop appliances,
lamps, linens,

08:30.093 --> 08:31.677
your TV.

08:32.220 --> 08:33.846
The backpack should be
getting pretty heavy now.

08:33.929 --> 08:35.556
And you go bigger.

08:35.640 --> 08:39.684
Your couch, bed, your kitchen table.
Stuff it all in there.

08:39.769 --> 08:41.854
Your car, get it in there.

08:42.188 --> 08:46.692
Your home, whether it's a studio apartment 
or a two-bedroom house,

08:46.776 --> 08:49.862
I want you to stuff it all
into that backpack.

08:51.907 --> 08:53.574
Now try to walk.

08:55.577 --> 08:57.453
It's kind of hard, isn't it?

08:58.205 --> 09:00.164
This is what we do to ourselves
on a daily basis.

09:00.248 --> 09:03.042
We weigh ourselves down
until we can't even move.

09:03.126 --> 09:06.462
And make no mistake, moving is living.

09:07.297 --> 09:09.840
Now, I'm gonna set that backpack on fire.

09:09.925 --> 09:12.801
What do you want to take out of it?
Photos?

09:13.470 --> 09:15.054
Photos are for people
who can't remember.

09:15.138 --> 09:17.848
Drink some ginkgo
and let the photos burn.

09:18.266 --> 09:23.812
In fact, let everything burn and imagine
waking up tomorrow with nothing.

09:25.774 --> 09:28.400
It's kind of exhilarating, isn't it?

09:35.533 --> 09:37.368
Welcome back, Mr. Bingham.

09:47.170 --> 09:48.254
Ryan Bingham's office.

09:48.338 --> 09:50.589
You put me in a Dodge Stratus
in Kansas City.

09:50.674 --> 09:52.633
They were completely out 
of all full-size sedans.

09:52.717 --> 09:53.801
- Did you try...
- <i>Yes.</i>

09:53.885 --> 09:55.594
<i>I reminded them of your remarkable</i>

09:55.679 --> 09:57.721
No.1 Gold Club status
and years in the program.

09:57.806 --> 10:01.016
They are literally moving mountains
to see you in a Sebring.

10:01.434 --> 10:03.269
Fair enough. 
Any other messages?

10:03.353 --> 10:04.478
<i>Your sister Kara called.</i>

10:04.562 --> 10:06.939
Needs to speak urgently
about your sister's wedding.

10:07.023 --> 10:10.317
I told her you were mid-air 
and not even I knew your final destination.

10:10.652 --> 10:12.152
- Well done.
- <i>And you got an invitation</i>

10:12.237 --> 10:14.238
to speak at Goalquest in Vegas.

10:15.907 --> 10:17.032
Goalquest 20?

10:17.284 --> 10:20.703
<i>Every once in a while, I do speaking engagements, 
motivational kind of stuff.</i>

10:20.787 --> 10:24.415
<i>But Goalquest?
We're talking major Tony Robbins shit.</i>

10:24.708 --> 10:26.542
It's got a hologram on it.

10:26.626 --> 10:29.253
They're calling it Dos Equis.

10:29.337 --> 10:30.421
All right, I'll check in.

10:30.505 --> 10:33.173
- Hold on. I've got Craig Gregory for you.
- Wait...

10:33.258 --> 10:34.383
Fuck.

10:35.302 --> 10:37.261
How is my little road warrior?

10:37.345 --> 10:40.472
Hey, 20 minutes from boarding
into a world of bliss.

10:40.557 --> 10:42.725
Real good numbers out of Phoenix,
Ry guy.

10:42.809 --> 10:44.643
Hey, you know that Big Auto
is about to cut

10:44.728 --> 10:46.353
another 10K 
before the end of the month?

10:46.479 --> 10:48.147
- No kidding.
- Yeah. Christmas came early.

10:48.231 --> 10:49.940
I wish I could have you
in about five places at once,

10:50.025 --> 10:51.859
but I do need you back here in Omaha
by the end of week.

10:51.943 --> 10:53.694
- All right?
- I thought you needed me everywhere.

10:53.862 --> 10:56.989
Well, you know, we got something
real big here, a real game changer.

10:57.073 --> 10:58.324
What are we talking about here?

10:58.408 --> 11:04.121
You'll see. Today I took my first crap
in two weeks, hallelujah.

11:04.205 --> 11:06.749
- That's me hanging up on you.
- Great, love that sound.

11:27.062 --> 11:29.104
Are you satisfied with Maestro?

11:32.442 --> 11:33.942
Yeah, I am.

11:34.652 --> 11:36.987
A little stingy with their miles.
I like Hertz.

11:37.072 --> 11:39.239
No, Hertz keeps its vehicles too long.

11:39.324 --> 11:42.159
If a car has over 20,000 miles,
I won't drive it.

11:42.952 --> 11:46.413
Maestro doesn't instant checkout.
I like to park and go.

11:46.498 --> 11:48.290
Hertz doesn't guarantee navigation.

11:48.375 --> 11:50.542
It's funny. You don't seem like a girl
who needs directions.

11:50.627 --> 11:54.630
I hate asking for directions.
That's why I get a nav.

11:56.883 --> 11:59.593
That new outfit, Colonial, isn't bad.

12:01.679 --> 12:03.347
- Is that a joke?
- Yes.

12:03.431 --> 12:06.892
- Because their kiosk placement blows.
- They never have available upgrades.

12:06.976 --> 12:08.727
Basically, it's a fleet of shit-boxes.

12:08.812 --> 12:11.230
I don't know 
how they're still in business.

12:11.314 --> 12:13.399
- I'm Ryan.
- I'm Alex.

12:18.530 --> 12:19.655
Maplewood card.

12:19.739 --> 12:22.241
How dare you bring that
into this palace?

12:22.325 --> 12:23.951
Hilton offers equal value and better food,

12:24.035 --> 12:26.245
but the Maplewood gives out
warm cookies at check-in.

12:26.329 --> 12:27.538
They got you with the cookies, did they?

12:27.622 --> 12:29.706
Yeah. I'm a sucker 
for simulated hospitality.

12:29.791 --> 12:31.417
You know,
there's an industry term for that.

12:31.501 --> 12:35.003
It's a mixture of "faux" and "homey." 
"Faumey."

12:36.297 --> 12:37.673
Oh, my God.

12:37.757 --> 12:40.259
I wasn't sure this actually existed.

12:40.343 --> 12:42.261
This is the American Airlines...

12:42.345 --> 12:44.596
It's a Concierge Key, yeah.

12:48.518 --> 12:51.437
- What is that, carbon fiber?
- Graphite.

12:51.521 --> 12:52.938
Oh, God, I love the weight.

12:53.022 --> 12:55.107
I was pretty excited the day
that bad boy came in.

12:55.191 --> 12:56.942
Yeah. I'll say.

12:57.026 --> 12:59.236
I put up pretty pedestrian numbers.

12:59.320 --> 13:01.530
Sixty thou a year, domestic.

13:02.157 --> 13:04.450
- That's not bad.
- Don't patronize me.

13:04.534 --> 13:06.285
- What's your total?
- It's a personal question.

13:06.369 --> 13:07.953
- Oh, please.
- And we hardly know each other.

13:08.037 --> 13:11.540
Come on. Show some hubris.
Come on, impress me.

13:13.334 --> 13:15.711
- I bet it's huge.
- You have no idea.

13:16.212 --> 13:17.546
How big?

13:17.714 --> 13:19.673
What is it, this big?

13:20.216 --> 13:22.134
- This big?
- I don't want to brag.

13:22.218 --> 13:24.178
Come on! Come on.

13:24.679 --> 13:28.515
Let's just say I have a number in mind.
I haven't hit it yet.

13:31.644 --> 13:33.395
This is pretty fucking sexy.

13:33.480 --> 13:36.023
Hope it doesn't cheapen our relationship.

13:36.524 --> 13:38.734
We're two people who get turned on
by elite status.

13:38.818 --> 13:41.111
I think cheap is our starting point.

13:41.196 --> 13:43.405
There's nothing cheap about loyalty.

13:47.035 --> 13:50.871
So, we came up with this master plan,
which was for me

13:51.664 --> 13:56.126
to put gauze,
to put bandages on both my hands.

13:56.753 --> 13:58.545
Then we got on the plane,

13:58.630 --> 14:02.007
transatlantic, flying to Zürich.

14:02.509 --> 14:04.301
Walked up... 
Waited till it was dark,

14:04.385 --> 14:06.887
and walked up to the bathroom with her.

14:06.971 --> 14:09.640
Everybody was watching the movie,
and I was like...

14:09.724 --> 14:11.433
Opened up, went inside.

14:11.518 --> 14:13.060
She opened the door for me,

14:13.144 --> 14:14.978
and came in
like she was gonna help me.

14:15.063 --> 14:17.356
And then, you know, we gave it
our best shot. It wasn't great.

14:17.440 --> 14:19.233
But it was fun. 
It was tricky.

14:19.317 --> 14:21.527
- Give me some details.
- Well, it's not so easy.

14:21.611 --> 14:24.404
- Have you ever tried it? It's not so easy.
- Yes, I have.

14:26.282 --> 14:28.075
- Really?
- Really.

14:33.790 --> 14:35.874
- You've done that?
- I have done that.

14:36.417 --> 14:38.085
On a transatlantic flight?

14:38.169 --> 14:41.088
On a domestic flight. 
Regional, actually.

14:41.172 --> 14:42.965
- Like nighttime?
- No, like daytime.

14:43.049 --> 14:44.925
- You...
- What?

14:45.301 --> 14:46.426
I mean, how do you do that?

14:46.511 --> 14:48.512
I'm really flexible.

14:52.684 --> 14:53.976
Look.

15:00.358 --> 15:02.359
I should throw these out.

15:06.114 --> 15:08.574
We can always use that room
with the ice machine.

15:08.658 --> 15:10.033
Here, look.

15:26.342 --> 15:28.677
Good call on that towel rack.

15:28.761 --> 15:31.138
I like how you burritoed me
in the sofa cushions.

15:31.222 --> 15:32.973
I was improvising.

15:33.641 --> 15:36.101
Shame we didn't make it to the closet.

15:37.061 --> 15:39.187
- We got to do this again.
- Yeah.

15:44.569 --> 15:48.363
All right, I'm in Newark on the 12th,
Modesto on the 13th,

15:49.073 --> 15:51.033
Oklahoma City on the 15th.

15:51.117 --> 15:54.453
Any Southwest? I'll be swinging 
by Albuquerque week of the 16th.

15:54.537 --> 15:56.330
No, but I'll be in Florida on the 20th.

15:56.414 --> 15:58.457
- Fort Lauderdale?
- Miami.

15:58.875 --> 16:00.542
- That's nothing.
- Forty minutes.

16:11.220 --> 16:14.473
I should probably go back to my room
so I can wake up in my bed.

16:14.557 --> 16:17.017
I think that would be
the ladylike thing to do.

16:25.068 --> 16:26.735
Nice meeting you.

16:27.070 --> 16:28.570
A pleasure.

17:03.439 --> 17:06.148
- Hello?
- <i>Hey, Ryan, how you holding up?</i>  

17:06.233 --> 17:09.944
<i>Every family has the one person
who keeps the genealogy in check.</i>

17:10.029 --> 17:12.196
<i>That's my sister Kara, the glue.</i>

17:12.573 --> 17:14.782
Fine. You and the kids?

17:15.367 --> 17:18.954
Missy's outstanding, Matthew made varsity. 
How's the road?

17:19.038 --> 17:21.665
- Couldn't be better.
- <i>Good. So, Ryan?</i>

17:22.750 --> 17:23.709
Yeah?

17:23.792 --> 17:25.210
<i>I didn't even want to have 
to ask you this</i>

17:25.294 --> 17:28.463
because I know how you are
about doing things for others,

17:28.548 --> 17:31.174
<i>but we're coming up on three weeks
to go to Julie's wedding</i>

17:31.259 --> 17:33.218
and there's something
we could really use your help on.

17:33.302 --> 17:34.344
Yeah?

17:34.429 --> 17:36.096
<i>We've been sending people these kits</i>

17:36.180 --> 17:38.765
so they can print out photos
of Julie and Jim on cardboard 

17:38.850 --> 17:41.351
and then take photos of them
in interesting places,

17:41.436 --> 17:43.145
kind of like that gnome
in the French movie.

17:43.229 --> 17:44.271
Why?

17:44.939 --> 17:47.399
Because it's Julie's wedding
and she thinks it would be fun.

17:47.483 --> 17:49.985
- Does it matter why?
- How is Julie?

17:50.194 --> 17:51.987
<i>Would you call her?
She thinks you've turned to butter.</i>

17:52.071 --> 17:54.239
You're awfully isolated the way you live.

17:54.323 --> 17:56.116
Isolated? I'm surrounded.

17:56.200 --> 17:58.702
<i>So, your assistant said
you were gonna be in Vegas.</i>

17:58.786 --> 17:59.786
Did he?

17:59.871 --> 18:03.749
Can you get a photo of the cutout
in front of the Luxor pyramid?

18:03.833 --> 18:05.834
The place is a shithole.
Nobody stays there.

18:06.461 --> 18:08.712
Jesus, Ryan,
I'm not asking you to check in.

18:08.796 --> 18:10.922
Can you just take a stupid photo?

18:11.549 --> 18:13.258
I'll try my best.

18:13.634 --> 18:16.011
<i>Thank you for trying your best.</i>

18:34.906 --> 18:38.200
<i>Last year, 
I spent 322 days on the road,</i>

18:38.284 --> 18:41.745
<i>which means I had to spend
43 miserable days at home.</i>

19:06.187 --> 19:07.813
Hey, neighbor.

19:08.064 --> 19:09.481
Hey. Hi!

19:10.233 --> 19:12.734
Hi. Hey, I signed for this
while you were gone.

19:12.902 --> 19:14.402
Thanks.

19:15.655 --> 19:17.906
- I hope it wasn't too much of a bother.
- Nah.

19:22.787 --> 19:23.912
Wow.

19:24.080 --> 19:28.083
Yeah, it's my sister. I haven't met
the guy yet. They're getting married.

19:28.584 --> 19:30.585
- Lots of luck.
- I know, right?

19:31.087 --> 19:34.130
What are you doing tonight?
You wanna come over later?

19:36.926 --> 19:38.760
I've started seeing somebody.

19:39.595 --> 19:41.429
Okay. Great.

19:43.266 --> 19:44.975
Hey, it's good to see you.

19:45.810 --> 19:49.229
- You, too.
- It seems like it's been a while this time.

20:03.703 --> 20:04.870
Okay.

20:07.164 --> 20:09.541
I am just... I'm thrilled that
everyone's back under one roof.

20:09.625 --> 20:10.792
Welcome home, boys.

20:11.127 --> 20:13.169
I know there's been a lot of whispering
about why we're here,

20:13.254 --> 20:17.591
so let me jump right in.
Retailers are down 20%.

20:17.675 --> 20:20.093
Auto industry is in the dump.

20:20.177 --> 20:22.512
Housing market doesn't have a heartbeat.

20:22.597 --> 20:25.891
It is one of the worst times 
on record for America.

20:27.059 --> 20:29.477
This is our moment.

20:30.938 --> 20:34.065
Now, last summer, we received
a dynamite young woman here

20:34.150 --> 20:35.901
from Cornell,

20:35.985 --> 20:39.404
and she had some pretty big ideas
that she challenged me with.

20:39.488 --> 20:42.032
And my first reaction was,
"Who does this kid think that she is?"

20:42.116 --> 20:44.409
But after I gave it a listen,
she really knocked me out.

20:44.493 --> 20:48.330
So, with a peek into our future,
Natalie Keener.

20:51.667 --> 20:54.753
If there's one word I want to
leave you with today, it's this.

20:57.757 --> 20:59.049
"Glocal"?

21:00.593 --> 21:01.885
Glocal.

21:02.303 --> 21:05.180
Our global must become local.

21:06.474 --> 21:11.227
This company keeps 23 people
on the road at least 250 days a year.

21:11.896 --> 21:14.522
It's expensive, and it's inefficient.

21:14.899 --> 21:17.776
When I came to Craig
three months ago with this,

21:17.860 --> 21:22.447
he told me, and quite astutely,
it's only a problem if you have a solution.

21:22.531 --> 21:25.617
Well, today I stand before you
with just that.

21:27.203 --> 21:30.914
You all know Ned in reception.
Today I'm gonna fire Ned.

21:32.291 --> 21:35.460
Sorry, Ned. I'm sure HR
will hire you back this afternoon.

21:35.544 --> 21:37.337
We'll see about that.

21:38.047 --> 21:42.258
Now Ned could be any employee in any one 
of our clients' locations worldwide.

21:42.343 --> 21:44.469
Strategy packets 
will be shipped in advance.

21:44.553 --> 21:45.553
Ned would be given a seat

21:45.638 --> 21:48.556
and find one of our transition specialists
waiting for him.

21:49.684 --> 21:52.560
Mr. Laskin, the reason
we're having this conversation

21:52.645 --> 21:54.729
is your position is no longer available.

